Document: Adding a camera  
Path: godot/getting_started/03.player_movement_code.rst  
Summary: This section explains how to set up a camera rig with a pivot and configure an orthographic projection for the player's view.  

Let's add the camera next. Like we did with the Player's Pivot, create a basic rig by right-clicking the Main node and selecting *Add Child Node*. Create a new Marker3D and name it CameraPivot. Add a child node Camera3D to CameraPivot. Your scene tree should now have a CameraPivot parent node with a Camera3D child.  

The Preview checkbox in the 3D view's top-left lets you preview the in-game camera projection. Split the 3D view by selecting *View > 2 Viewports* (or press Ctrl + 2/Cmd + 2) to navigate the scene and see the camera's perspective. In the bottom viewport, select Camera3D and enable the Preview checkbox. In the top viewport, move the Camera3D 19 units along the Z axis (drag the blue arrow).  

Select CameraPivot and rotate it -45 degrees around the X axis (using the red circle). This simulates a crane-mounted camera. Press F6 (Cmd + R on macOS) to run the scene and test movement with arrow keys.  

The current perspective projection creates empty space around the character. Switch to an orthographic projection for a flatter, more readable view. Select Camera3D, set Projection to *Orthogonal*, and adjust Size to 19. The character will appear flatter, and the ground will fill the background.  

Note: When using an orthogonal camera in Godot 4, directional shadow quality depends on the camera's Far value. Higher Far values increase visibility distance but reduce shadow quality. If shadows appear blurry after switching to orthogonal, lower the Far value to 100 (avoid setting it too low to prevent distant objects from disappearing).  

Test your scene to ensure movement works in all 8 directions without glitching through the floor. Next, we'll work on implementing monsters.